# forge-provision optional Brewfile — apps tried and not currently relied on.
# Apply with: brew bundle install --file=manifests/Brewfile.optional
# Reference: https://github.com/Homebrew/homebrew-bundle
#
# Entries here are evaluation installs: useful enough to keep declared so a
# fresh Mac can opt in with one command, but not part of the baseline because
# they overlap with primary tools or carry costs (subscription, performance,
# duplication) that make them poor defaults. Move an entry back into
# manifests/Brewfile if it earns daily-driver status.

# Warp (Rust-based terminal with AI-assisted command-line features). Free
# tier is just a fast terminal; the differentiating AI / agent features sit
# behind a paid tier that overlaps with Claude Code Max. Kept here for
# occasional comparison runs. Reference: https://www.warp.dev/
cask "warp"

# Wave Terminal (open-source, Electron + React frontend with a Go backend).
# Carries the typical Electron weight (cold-start memory, redraw lag) and
# the renderer is not GPU-accelerated like Ghostty's. Worth installing when
# you want graphical blocks (inline image previews, embedded HTML reports,
# database-browser plugin). Skip for daily driving on this Mac.
# Reference: https://www.waveterm.dev/
cask "wave"
